<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="23.[189,454,1328,1354]" box="[189,454,1328,1354]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,454,1328,1354]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,454,1328,1354]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Differential diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[188,1400,1376,1580]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<taxonomicName authority="Barkalov &amp; Ståhls, 2022" authorityName="Barkalov &amp; Ståhls" authorityYear="2022" box="[189,673,1376,1402]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Cheilosia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevimontana" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Montanocheila">
<emphasis box="[189,301,1376,1402]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Cheilosia</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[318,496,1376,1402]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Montanocheila</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[511,673,1376,1402]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">brevimontana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[680,769,1376,1402]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
has a strikingly dense pilosity of the body. Among the Nepalese taxa 
<taxonomicName authority="Barkalov &amp; Ståhls, 2022" authorityName="Barkalov &amp; Ståhls" authorityYear="2022" box="[355,609,1411,1438]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Cheilosia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevimontana" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Montanocheila">
<emphasis box="[355,382,1412,1438]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">C.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[399,432,1412,1437]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">M.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[447,609,1411,1437]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">brevimontana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[613,702,1412,1438]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Barkalov &amp; Ståhls, 2022" authorityName="Barkalov &amp; Ståhls" authorityYear="2022" box="[912,1084,1411,1438]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Cheilosia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigella" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Montanocheila">
<emphasis box="[912,939,1412,1438]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">C.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[956,988,1412,1437]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">M.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[1003,1084,1411,1437]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">nigella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1090,1182,1412,1438]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, for distinguishing characters see under 
<taxonomicName authority="Barkalov &amp; Ståhls, 2022" authorityName="Barkalov &amp; Ståhls" authorityYear="2022" box="[438,613,1447,1473]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Cheilosia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigella" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Montanocheila">
<emphasis box="[438,465,1447,1473]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">C.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[482,514,1448,1473]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">M.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[532,613,1447,1473]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">nigella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[622,714,1447,1473]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
From this and all other congeners the new species can be distinguished by the following combination of characters: broad frons and gena, basoflagellomere broader than long, dense mesonotal pilosity with admixed shorter yellowish and long black pilosity, and dense pollinosity on medial parts of scutum and scutellum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[189,1124,1619,1693]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="23.[189,324,1619,1645]" box="[189,324,1619,1645]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,1619,1645]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,1619,1645]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[189,1124,1666,1693]" box="[189,1124,1666,1693]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
The specific epithet is derived from the Latin ‘ 
<emphasis box="[735,806,1666,1692]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">brevis</emphasis>
’, meaning ‘short’ or ‘low’.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
